  ∴ Explain the concept clearly and completely...

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield explanation ≡ "Confluence means that when a Cell program has multiple cells ready to execute at the same time, it doesn't matter which one you pick first — you get the same final result either way. This works because Cell's execution model is monotonic: once a cell produces an output, that output is frozen and never changes. Since cells only read each other's frozen outputs (never modifying them), two independent cells can't interfere with each other. Think of it like filling in a crossword puzzle — it doesn't matter whether you solve 3-across or 7-down first, because each answer is determined by its clue, not by which other squares you filled in first. This matters because it means Cell programs can be safely parallelized: you can run multiple cells simultaneously without locks, race conditions, or coordination overhead. It also means debugging is simpler — if something goes wrong, the execution order is irrelevant."

  yield jargon-terms ≡ [
    "confluence",
    "monotonic",
    "frozen",
    "execution model",
    "race conditions",
    "parallelized",
    "DAG (directed acyclic graph)"
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ explanation addresses "how" and "why" → ✓ (how: monotonic frozen outputs; why: safe parallelism)
--   ⊨ explanation is 3-8 sentences → ✓ (6 sentences)
--   ⊨ length(jargon-terms) ≥ 1 → ✓ (7)

