  yield final-explanation

-- LLM evaluation (simulated):

  yield final-explanation ≡ "
# How Does Cell's Confluence Property Work and Why Does It Matter?

## The Main Idea

Confluence means that when a Cell program has multiple cells ready to execute at the same time, it doesn't matter which one you pick first — you get the same final result either way. This works because Cell's execution model is monotonic: once a cell produces an output, that output is frozen and never changes. Since cells only read each other's frozen outputs (never modifying them), two independent cells can't interfere with each other.

Think of it like filling in a crossword puzzle — it doesn't matter whether you solve 3-across or 7-down first, because each answer is determined by its clue, not by which other squares you filled in first.

This matters because it means Cell programs can be safely run in parallel: you can run multiple cells at the same time without them stepping on each other's toes. It also means debugging is simpler — if something goes wrong, the order things happened in is irrelevant.

## Digging Deeper

### What does 'monotonic' mean?
Monotonic means 'only goes one direction.' Think of filling a glass of water — you can add water, but you can't un-add it. The glass only gets fuller, never emptier. In Cell, answers only get filled in, never erased. Once a cell figures out its answer, that answer stays forever.

### What is an 'execution model'?
An execution model is the set of rules for how a program does its work — like the rules of a board game. In Monopoly, the rules say you roll dice, move your piece, and follow the instructions on the square. Cell's rules say: look at all the cells, find ones that have all the information they need, pick one, let it do its work, write down the answer, then repeat.

### What are 'race conditions'?
A race condition is when two workers try to change the same thing at the same time and the result depends on who gets there first. Imagine two kids both trying to write the answer to a math problem on the whiteboard at the same time — you get a mess. Cell avoids this because workers never change something already written. They only write in blank spaces, and each blank space has exactly one correct answer.

## The One-Sentence Version

When a Cell program has several things it could do next, it doesn't matter which one it does first — like a crossword puzzle where every clue has exactly one answer, so you always end up with the same completed grid no matter what order you solve the clues.
"

