--
-- Input: 1 technical question
-- Output: layered explanation with 3 sub-explanations + 1-sentence summary
-- Jargon terms identified: 7, classified: 4 clear + 3 hard
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: comprehension oracle naturally controls recursion depth
--   The "would a 10-year-old understand?" oracle on sub-explain-template
--   returned still-hard = false for all 3 terms after one level of
--   decomposition. No term required deeper recursion. The oracle acts as
--   a natural stopping condition: simple concepts terminate at depth 1,
--   complex ones would recurse to depth 2 or 3. The max=3 bound on ⊢∘
--   prevents pathological cases where every explanation introduces new jargon.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: analogy is the leaf node of explanation
--   Every successful leaf explanation (still-hard = false) used an analogy:
--   glass of water (monotonic), board game rules (execution model),
--   kids at whiteboard (race conditions). The comprehension oracle implicitly
--   selects for analogies — they're the simplest way to make abstract
--   concepts concrete. This suggests analogies are the "crystallized"
--   form of explanations: they map abstract to concrete deterministically.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: the spawner creates a natural explanation tree
--   concept → [monotonic, execution-model, race-conditions] forms a tree.
--   Each branch is independent (confluence!). If any branch had returned
--   still-hard = true, the ⊢∘ loop would spawn sub-sub-explainers,
--   deepening that branch while leaving converged branches untouched.
--   The tree grows only where comprehension fails — minimum explanation.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: the program demonstrates its own subject matter
--   This Cell program about confluence IS confluent: frames 4-6 (the three
--   explainer cells) are independent and can execute in any order. The
--   trace proves confluence by exhibiting it — the explanation of a property
--   is itself an instance of that property. This is Cell's metacircular
--   character in action.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: assess-comprehension separates generation from evaluation
--   The explain cell generates the explanation (NP-hard creative work).
--   The assess-comprehension cell evaluates it (P-time judgment). This is
--   the proof-carrying pattern applied to pedagogy: the LLM creates, then
--   a separate oracle checks. Neither cell is biased by the other — the
--   explainer doesn't know which terms will be flagged, and the assessor
--   doesn't know what analogies will be used in sub-explanations.
